''Rambo'' was well received. Your Sinclair described it as "a thinking man's ''Commando''. That game starts fast and gets faster until you end up like a one-man whirlwind. Rambo develops into a solid shoot'em up".

''Rambo'' replaced ''Commando'' as the number one game in the Gallup ZX Spectrum chart<ref name='pcw9jan86charts'>{{cite magazine |title=Charts|magazine=Popular Computing Weekly|issue=2|publisher=Sunshine Publications|date=9 January 1986|page=35|url=https://spectrumcomputing.co.uk/page.php?issue_id=2890&page=35|access-date=9 March 2023}}</ref> and did the same on the Commodore 64 and All Formats charts the following week.<ref name='pcw16jan86charts'>{{cite magazine |title=Charts|magazine=Popular Computing Weekly|issue=3|publisher=Sunshine Publications|date=16 January 1986|page=35|url=https://spectrumcomputing.co.uk/page.php?issue_id=2891&page=35|access-date=9 March 2023}}</ref> The Amstrad CPC version also went to number one eight weeks later, replacing ''[[Yie Ar Kung Fu]]''.<ref name='pcw13mar86charts'>{{cite magazine |title=Charts|magazine=Popular Computing Weekly|issue=11|publisher=Sunshine Publications|date=13 March 1986|page=35|url=https://spectrumcomputing.co.uk/page.php?issue_id=2899&page=35|access-date=9 March 2023}}</ref>

The Amstrad CPC and ZX Spectrum versions of the game were included on the 1986 compilation ''They Sold a Million 3'',<ref name="spectrumcomputing">{{cite web|url=https://spectrumcomputing.co.uk/index.php?cat=96&id=11373|title=They Sold a Million 3|publisher=Spectrum Computing|accessdate=2023-06-14}}</ref><ref name="mobygames">{{cite web|url=http://www.mobygames.com/game/they-sold-a-million-3|title=They Sold a Million 3 for Amstrad CPC (1986) - MobyGames|publisher=mobygames.com|accessdate=2015-09-05}}</ref> along with ''Fighter Pilot'', ''[[Ghostbusters (1984 video game)|Ghostbusters]]'', and ''[[Kung-Fu Master (video game)|Kung-Fu Master]]''.

In 1989, Ocean released the game alongside ''[[Daley Thompson's Decathlon]]'' and ''[[Enduro Racer]]'' as one of the launch titles for their new budget range, The Hit Squad.<ref name='nce6may89'>{{cite magazine |title=Ocean Hit Squad: Collect the set|magazine=New Computer Express|issue=26|publisher=Future Publishing|date=6 May 1989|page=2|url=https://spectrumcomputing.co.uk/page.php?issue_id=4798&page=2|access-date=9 March 2023}}</ref><ref name='sinclairuserjuly89'>{{cite magazine |title=A Big Drop in the Ocean|magazine=Sinclair User|issue=88|publisher=EMAP|date=18 June 1989|page=22|url=https://spectrumcomputing.co.uk/page.php?issue_id=88&page=22|access-date=9 March 2023}}</ref> It reached number 4 in the All Formats Budget Games chart.<ref name='nce22july89charts'>{{cite magazine |title=Top Ten Budget Games|magazine=New Computer Express|issue=37|publisher=Future Publishing|date=22 July 1989|page=5|url=https://archive.org/details/NH2021_New_Computer_Express_Issue037.pdf/page/n3|access-date=9 March 2023}}</ref>

